  <h1 id="artHead">COVID-19 SCHOOL SHUTDOWN UPDATE - April 17th, 2020</h1>

     
  <div id="bylineDateBox">
        </div>
<!-- /bylineDateBox -->

  
    <p><strong><span style="font-size:16px;">COVID-19 School Shutdown Update<br>
April 17, 2020<br><br>
As you may have heard, this afternoon Illinois Governor Pritzker announced that in-person learning has been suspended for the remainder of this school year. Illinois now joins 27 other states that have already made the same decision. District 102 will continue to operate using its Remote Learning Plan for the rest of the 2019-20 school year. Our staff remains committed to providing learning activities and working to remain engaged with all students through the Remote Learning Process. Additionally, I can assure you that our food distribution program will continue to serve our students who need daily meals. <br><br>
With the Governor's announcement today, there will be some changes to our school calendar for the rest of the year. When the state created the term Remote Learning Days at the end of March, it also granted districts the usage of five of their remaining school calendar days to be used as Remote Planning Days. The planning days are to be used at the district's discretion. District 102 will be using these five planning days the week of May 18-22. This was originally scheduled to be the last week of classes for District 102 students. Therefore, the last Remote Learning Day for all the students will now be Friday, May 15. District 102 staff will use the week of May 18-22 to collect materials from students including assignments and any hardware distributed to students for usage during the shutdown. This week of May 18-22 will also be used by District 102 staff to engage in end-of-the year planning activities in wishful preparation for a return to a normal schedule next fall. The fi nal day of responsibility for District 102 staff will continue to be Tuesday, May 26, which is still scheduled as a Teacher Institute Day on the 2019-20 school calendar.<br><br>
The calendar changes outlined in the previous paragraph are not the only changes we will experience. Today’s announcement will result in other scheduling changes throughout the remainder of the year. Those changes have yet to be determined. Over the course of the upcoming weeks, our staff will need to meet and sort out the details for multiple end-of-the year events that are currently scheduled. Some of those events will surely be cancelled, but we will work together to create opportunities to continue with other events, such as awards ceremonies and graduation, for example, in some alternative form, if possible. Please be patient as we work together to finalize these plans. Once finalized, we will work to share that information with you when it is available.<br><br>
We are saddened by the reality that our school community will not be able to reconvene in person this school year due to this public health crisis. Many people have worked so hard in both the classroom and in extracurricular activities that today’s announcement feels like a step back. Fortunately, the final chapter of this school year hasn’t been written yet. We plan to make the most of the remaining time. This shutdown has proven that our school community is resilient, capable and compassionate. I’m confident that there is still time for our students and staff to shine the remainder of the school year.<br><br>
I can't thank you enough for all that you are doing as we all work together through this. This period of Remote Learning offers us new ways to learn and grow. I am confident that we will emerge stronger. <br><br>
Byron Sondgeroth, Superintendent<br>
North Pekin-Marquette Heights School District 102</span></strong></p>

